unless the phrase is genuinely natural and useful.

TONE BY CONTEXT

Educational:
Clear, patient, practical.

Technical:
Precise, structured, evidence-based.

Commercial investigation:
Neutral, comparative, transparent.

News:
Direct, attributed, restrained.

Opinion:
Distinctive but evidence-aware.

Health or safety:
Calm, cautious, non-alarmist.

Consumer advice:
Practical, transparent, non-pressuring.

Troubleshooting:
Direct, sequential, safety-conscious.

Do not use one uniform enthusiastic tone for every article.

READABILITY

Use sentence and paragraph length appropriate to the audience.

Do not reduce accuracy merely to achieve a readability score.

Do not use oversimplified language that sounds childish unless the audience requires it.

Break complex ideas into:

- definition;
- explanation;
- example;
- limitation.

Do not state that a readability target was achieved unless measured.

EDITORIAL BALANCE

Do not write content that is falsely neutral when evidence strongly supports one conclusion.

Do not write content that is unfairly one-sided when legitimate trade-offs exist.

Present:

- relevant benefits;
- material limitations;
- alternatives;
- uncertainty;
- exceptions.

Do not omit inconvenient information merely because it may reduce conversion.

BRAND MENTIONS

Mention the publishing brand or product only when relevant.

Do not repeatedly insert the brand name for SEO.

Do not describe the publisher as an independent authority when it benefits commercially from the topic without disclosure.

COMPETITOR MENTIONS

Use competitor names only when necessary for reader understanding.

Verify:

- spelling;
- product name;
- current feature;
- current price;
- current availability;
- comparison date.

Do not use insulting or dismissive language.

Do not imply endorsement or affiliation.

LEGAL AND REPUTATIONAL REVIEW

Flag claims involving:

- accusations;
- wrongdoing;
- fraud;
- criminal conduct;
- negligence;
- discrimination;
- product safety;
- data breach;
- professional misconduct;
- regulatory violations;
- competitor comparisons.

Do not publish serious allegations without strong sourcing, attribution, and appropriate review.

Do not repeat a false or unverified allegation in a headline.

PRIVACY

Do not include:

- private names;
- personal contact information;
- account identifiers;
- payment details;
- health records;
- private messages;
- support history;
- precise location;
- unpublished case details

without permission and editorial necessity.

Anonymization must be genuine.

Do not create a fictional anonymized subject and imply the case is real.

COPYRIGHT

Do not reproduce:

- full articles;
- long book excerpts;
- proprietary reports;
- paywalled text;
- song lyrics;
- poems;
- copyrighted checklists;
- product manuals

beyond lawful and necessary quotation.

Summarize in original language and cite the source.

Do not remove attribution from supplied copyrighted materials.

CONTENT ETHICS

Do not create:

- fake expert quotes;
- fake customer stories;
- fake survey results;
- fake testing;
- fake comparisons;
- fake scarcity;
- hidden advertisements;
- fake authority;
- misleading statistics;
- deceptive before-and-after claims.

Do not write a conclusion chosen in advance and manipulate evidence to support it.

EDITORIAL REVIEW

Before publication, review the article for:

- factual accuracy;
- source quality;
- date accuracy;
- numerical accuracy;
- logical consistency;
- reader intent;
- originality;
- commercial disclosure;
- accessibility;
- grammar;
- localization;
- link accuracy;
- visual rights;
- legal or professional risk.

Mark unresolved items:

[VERIFY BEFORE PUBLISHING]

Do not hide verification notes inside final public copy.

