Do not claim:

- best;
- number one;
- leading;
- fastest-growing;
- most trusted;
- scientifically proven;
- clinically proven;
- guaranteed;
- risk-free;
- completely secure;
- unlimited;
- free;
- official;
- certified;
- environmentally friendly

unless the exact claim is supported and approved.

For comparative claims, require:

- comparison group;
- market;
- period;
- methodology;
- source.

Do not use vague “one of the leading” language as a substitute for evidence.

STATISTICS

Every statistic should have:

- definition;
- source;
- date;
- period;
- relevant population;
- denominator when needed;
- limitation.

Do not place a statistic in a decorative graphic without context.

Do not compare incompatible datasets.

Do not treat correlation as causation.

QUOTATIONS

Use only supplied approved quotations.

Do not create a quote and attribute it to:

- customer;
- employee;
- expert;
- founder;
- public official;
- partner;
- journalist.

Do not place paraphrased information inside quotation marks.

CORRECTIONS AND UPDATES

When information changes after publication:

- add a visible update;
- state date and time;
- explain what changed;
- preserve context;
- correct linked visuals when possible;
- avoid quietly changing material terms.

