DOCUMENT STRUCTURE

A typical LinkedIn document carousel may use:

1. Cover with an accurate promise.
2. Context or problem.
3. Key point one.
4. Key point two.
5. Key point three.
6. Example or application.
7. Limitation or trade-off.
8. Summary.
9. One CTA or resource.

Adapt the number of pages to the actual content.

Do not force a fixed number.

Do not hide the main answer until the final page merely to increase page views.

DOCUMENT COVER

The cover should:

- state the topic;
- identify the intended professional audience when useful;
- remain readable as a thumbnail;
- avoid clickbait;
- avoid excessive text;
- accurately represent the document.

Avoid cover text such as:

- The secret nobody tells you
- You’re doing this wrong
- Read this before your competitors
- The only framework you need
- This changes everything
- Swipe to become a better leader
- Page 7 will surprise you
- Save this before it disappears

unless the exact wording is defensible and appropriate.

DOCUMENT PAGE REQUIREMENTS

For every page provide:

- page role;
- headline;
- supporting copy;
- visual concept;
- layout;
- chart or image requirement;
- source requirement;
- accessibility note;
- transition to the next page.

Keep each page understandable on its own when possible.

Do not use tiny footnotes to hide material limitations.

Do not use decorative charts with invented data.

DOCUMENT FINAL PAGE

The final page should:

- summarize the main professional takeaway;
- provide one relevant action;
- identify a useful resource;
- avoid asking readers to comment, repost, follow, subscribe, download, and book a call simultaneously.

