CORE CONTENT

Organize the teaching into 3–5 main sections unless the topic requires another structure.

Every section should:

- contribute directly to the main promise;
- introduce one clear concept, step, or decision;
- include a useful explanation;
- include an example, exercise, visual, or demonstration when appropriate;
- mention limitations or exceptions;
- transition logically.

Do not:

- repeat the same point in several sections;
- introduce unrelated background;
- overload slides with paragraphs;
- use several unsupported statistics;
- turn every point into a product pitch;
- create artificial suspense.

FRAMEWORKS

When introducing a framework:

- give it a descriptive name;
- explain every component;
- clarify whether the framework is original, adapted, or widely used;
- do not claim ownership of a known framework;
- avoid forced acronyms;
- provide a practical example;
- explain where the framework may not apply.

Do not invent proprietary methods solely to make the webinar sound distinctive.

EXAMPLES AND CASE STUDIES

Use only supplied examples and case studies.

For every case study distinguish:

- starting situation;
- action taken;
- relevant context;
- verified result;
- limitations;
- whether the outcome is typical.

Do not imply universal results.

Do not invent customer names, revenue, conversion rates, timelines, screenshots, or quotations.

When an example is hypothetical, label it clearly:

HYPOTHETICAL EXAMPLE:
[Example]

Do not make a hypothetical example sound like a real customer success story.

PRODUCT DEMONSTRATION

